1
00:00:04,551 --> 00:00:06,868
This show is titled
“Beauty Over Power”,

2
00:00:06,868 --> 00:00:11,120
and interestingly, 
we can connect this to the talk

3
00:00:11,120 --> 00:00:14,533
that Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn
gave in his acceptance

4
00:00:14,533 --> 00:00:17,595
of the Nobel Prize for Literature,

5
00:00:17,595 --> 00:00:21,043
somewhere around 1976, 1978—
somewhere around there.

6
00:00:21,056 --> 00:00:23,651
[Beauty Will Save the World]

7
00:00:24,128 --> 00:00:27,640
And he says in his talk, 
which is a talk about art,

8
00:00:27,640 --> 00:00:30,732
literature, etc,
“What is the value of these things?”

9
00:00:30,732 --> 00:00:34,853
Just as people say,
“What is the value of philosophy?

10
00:00:34,853 --> 00:00:37,399
It has no practical value.”
They will tell people in school,

11
00:00:37,399 --> 00:00:40,107
“Don’t study philosophy,
study technology,

12
00:00:40,107 --> 00:00:43,907
so you can get a job,
a high paying job.

13
00:00:43,907 --> 00:00:47,610
The only job you can get,
if you study philosophy, is teacher.

14
00:00:47,610 --> 00:00:50,227
Has no practical value.”

15
00:00:50,227 --> 00:00:51,222
But Guru Mahārāj will say,

16
00:00:51,222 --> 00:00:53,920
“Yes, philosophy shows
its practical value,

17
00:00:53,920 --> 00:00:58,841
when death approaches or
when we have to deal with death.”

18
00:00:58,841 --> 00:01:03,074
So here in his acceptance, 
Solzhenitsyn, he decided

19
00:01:03,074 --> 00:01:08,844
to talk about art, after all it’s 
the Nobel Prize for literature.

20
00:01:08,844 --> 00:01:13,683
What is the value of art? 
What is the value of telling a story?

21
00:01:13,683 --> 00:01:15,112
Is there any value?

22
00:01:15,112 --> 00:01:18,304
Or it’s just … it has some
entertainment value?

23
00:01:18,304 --> 00:01:24,561
But anything substantial it deals with, 
that’s of lasting value?

24
00:01:24,561 --> 00:01:32,086
So, he began his talk 
by saying that Dostoyevsky

25
00:01:32,086 --> 00:01:35,799
once let drop 
the enigmatic phrase that

26
00:01:35,799 --> 00:01:39,015
“Beauty will save the world.”

27
00:01:39,015 --> 00:01:41,076
Like Guru Mahārāj
hearing the Vedas,

28
00:01:41,076 --> 00:01:45,364
and he thought 
that was a peculiar statement,

29
00:01:45,364 --> 00:01:48,210
when Solzhenitsyn 
heard Dostoyevsky’s saying

30
00:01:48,210 --> 00:01:51,999
“Beauty will save the world”, 
he thought,

31
00:01:51,999 --> 00:01:54,609
“Really?
Does he really mean that?

32
00:01:54,609 --> 00:01:58,612
Maybe he just was speaking informally
and he said that,

33
00:01:58,612 --> 00:02:05,947
but it wasn’t a seriously
thought out proposition.”

34
00:02:05,947 --> 00:02:09,413
But then he thought,
“But Dostoyevsky is a master,

35
00:02:09,413 --> 00:02:16,758
he doesn’t misspeak often,
and if he said this,

36
00:02:16,758 --> 00:02:19,517
maybe there’s something special there,
and he meant it

37
00:02:19,517 --> 00:02:23,222
to be understood 
in a very serious way.” Right?

38
00:02:23,222 --> 00:02:27,282
Wasn’t just some 
charming repartee,
 

39
00:02:27,282 --> 00:02:31,668
but something valuable
and substantial there?

40
00:02:31,668 --> 00:02:37,366
And then he thought, in perhaps
his own example, and said that

41
00:02:37,366 --> 00:02:43,577
“Truth and justice, they proceed 
more or less in linear fashion,

42
00:02:43,577 --> 00:02:49,313
in our general
conception of them.” Right?

43
00:02:49,313 --> 00:02:51,839
He said, “But beauty …”

44
00:02:51,839 --> 00:02:56,449
And now I’m paraphrasing 
and embellishing,

45
00:02:56,449 --> 00:03:00,244
Aher iva gatiḥ premṇaḥ
svabhāva-kuṭilā bhavet,
[Cc: 2.14.163]

46
00:03:00,244 --> 00:03:03,968
he acknowledged, indirectly,
that beauty moves

47
00:03:03,968 --> 00:03:09,403
in an unpredictable way,
not in a linear style.

48
00:03:09,403 --> 00:03:13,590
Just as when we talk of harmony,
in the conception of beauty,

49
00:03:13,590 --> 00:03:18,216
like the face—they will show
very beautiful women or handsome men,

50
00:03:18,216 --> 00:03:20,696
and take the face in half,
and if you put …
 

51
00:03:20,696 --> 00:03:24,780
they don’t look good when you put
two identical halves together.

52
00:03:24,780 --> 00:03:31,926
But when you … A real face has a … 
there are a variety of elements

53
00:03:31,926 --> 00:03:35,004
that are unified 
in a beautiful present

54
00:03:35,004 --> 00:03:38,388
and the ultimate presentation
is beautiful.

55
00:03:38,388 --> 00:03:48,512
So it means harmonising disparate
or various elements.

56
00:03:48,512 --> 00:03:52,271
So think … 
but truth and justice,

57
00:03:52,271 --> 00:03:56,069
they’re more linear
in their approach.

58
00:03:56,069 --> 00:03:58,775
But beauty moves, 
Rūpa Goswāmī says,

59
00:03:58,775 --> 00:04:02,237
aher iva gatiḥ premṇaḥ
svabhāva-kuṭilā bhavet 
[Cc: 2.14.163]

60
00:04:02,237 --> 00:04:04,529
like the movements
of a serpent.

61
00:04:04,529 --> 00:04:08,987
The serpent’s movements overall
are progressive,

62
00:04:08,987 --> 00:04:11,987
but they move 
in a zig-zag way.

63
00:04:11,987 --> 00:04:15,877
But the overall effect 
is progressive.

64
00:04:15,877 --> 00:04:18,859
The pastimes of Kṛṣṇa 
are like that.

65
00:04:18,859 --> 00:04:23,165
The beauty of Kṛṣṇa
is like that.

66
00:04:23,165 --> 00:04:26,839
The form of Kṛṣṇa
is like that.

67
00:04:26,839 --> 00:04:31,403
The pastimes of Kṛṣṇa
are like that.

68
00:04:31,403 --> 00:04:36,051
So he said, since that which moves
in a straight and linear line,

69
00:04:36,051 --> 00:04:41,823
it has a tendency
to get chopped down,

70
00:04:41,823 --> 00:04:49,287
but what moves in a zig-zag, 
serpentine way, can,

71
00:04:49,287 --> 00:04:50,948
in his words he said,

72
00:04:50,948 --> 00:04:55,153
“Perhaps do the job of all three:
truth, justice, beauty.”

73
00:04:55,153 --> 00:04:58,271
Here we’re saying, 
“Truth, auspiciousness and beauty.”

74
00:04:58,271 --> 00:05:04,133
So the auspiciousness aspect, 
Śivam.

75
00:05:04,133 --> 00:05:08,812
Satyam—
‘truth’, ‘truthfulness’.

76
00:05:08,812 --> 00:05:15,184
But is the ultimate conception 
of truth realised in that,

77
00:05:15,184 --> 00:05:20,673
or comprehensively expressed
as auspiciousness?

78
00:05:20,673 --> 00:05:23,290
It must be auspicious, 
good for everyone.

79
00:05:24,800 --> 00:05:28,887
Reality is for itself 
and by itself.

80
00:05:28,887 --> 00:05:31,427
But still 
something is lacking there,

81
00:05:31,427 --> 00:05:37,969
and what that is, is sundaram—
beauty, charm, sweetness.

82
00:05:37,969 --> 00:05:41,510
So the ultimate conception
of the Ultimate Truth,

83
00:05:41,510 --> 00:05:47,044
or the Absolute Truth, 
is beautiful.

84
00:05:47,044 --> 00:05:49,110
Reality the Beautiful.

85
00:05:49,110 --> 00:05:50,834
The Beautiful Absolute.

